    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Spare the Praise, Help the Child</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Darrel Mayers letter on Oct 18 says instead of using words to exact an effect on their children, parents should use spontaneous language of their hearts to praise their children</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New Advice for Parents: Saying 'That's Great!' May Not Be'' (news article, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>Lost in the discussion by these eminent pedagogues is the simple idea that instead of using words to exact an effect, parents use the spontaneous language of their hearts when their young ones show them their latest splashy Pollock.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''New Advice for Parents: Saying 'That's Great!' May Not Be'' (news article, Oct. 18):</p>
        <p>Lost in the discussion by these eminent pedagogues is the simple idea that instead of using words to exact an effect, parents use the spontaneous language of their hearts when their young ones show them their latest splashy Pollock.</p>
        <p>I suppose if this caught on, the experts might find themselves out of a job.</p>
        <p>DARREL MAYERS  Austin, Tex., Oct. 18, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
